original_title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - Horace Harding Boulevard
text:
Queens Boulevard, north side, at Horace Harding Boulevard, showing Heckmann's Halfway House. The original Halfway House is small structure on the left. The new house was built by Dietrich Muller. Mullers widow later married J. Tompkins, who lived nearby. The old house and the shed were torn down in late 1923 or early 1924. These houses stand on the line of the future Horace Harding Boulevard.

Views 1,2: 1922
View 3: April, 1923

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Queens Boulevard, north side, west of Eliot Ave., showing in their order from fore to background, the homes of J. Thompson, Mrs. S. Fox, and J. Geese in 1873. These homes were demolished when Queens Boulevard was widened.

April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Queens Boulevard, north side, opposite the east line of Eliot Ave., showing a group of old homes. The center house, No. 201, was at one time owned by Benj. Remsen.

April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster.

original_title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - Horace Harding Boulevard
text:
Queens Boulevard, north side, at Horace Harding Boulevard, showing the Halfway House with its extensions and porch removed. Queens Boulevard is being widened and the new street line marked off by the new dwelling seen in view 3. The Halfway House also stands in the line of the future Horace Harding Boulevard.

February, 1924
Views 1,2,3.
